        <owl:Class rdf:about="http://www.ebi.ac.uk/efo/EFO_1000012">          
            <obo:IAO_0000115>Loeys-Dietz syndrome-5 (LDS5), also known as     
  Rienhoff (pronounced REENhoff) syndrome, is characterized by syndromic      
  presentation of aortic aneurysms involving the thoracic and/or abdominal    
  aorta, with risk of dissection and rupture. Other systemic features include 
  cleft palate, bifid uvula, mitral valve disease, skeletal overgrowth,       
  cervical spine instability, and clubfoot deformity; however, not all        
  clinical features occur in all patients. In contrast to other forms of LDS, 
  no striking aortic or arterial tortuosity is present in these patients, and 
  there is no strong evidence for early aortic dissection.</obo:IAO_0000115>  
            <oboInOwl:hasDbXref>OMIM:615582</oboInOwl:hasDbXref>              
